"1280":"1280","Ruthven, Perthshire, Scotland":"Ruthven, Perthshire, Skotsko, United Kingdom"},"da":{"Abt 1280–17 October 1346":"omkring 1280–17. oktober 1346","1280–1346":"1280–1346","1321–1376":"1321–1376","1250–1330":"1250–1330","1346":"1346","17 October 1346":"17. oktober 1346","1376":"1376","1321":"1321","1330":"1330","1250":"1250","Abt 1280":"omkring 1280","1280":"1280","Ruthven, Perthshire, Scotland":"Ruthven, Perthshire, Skotland, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"Abt 1280–17 October 1346":"circa 1280–17 oktober 1346","1280–1346":"1280–1346","1321–1376":"1321–1376","1250–1330":"1250–1330","1346":"1346","17 October 1346":"17 oktober 1346","1376":"1376","1321":"1321","1330":"1330","1250":"1250","Abt 1280":"circa 1280","1280":"1280","Ruthven, Perthshire, Scotland":"Ruthven, Perthshire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Abt 1280–17 October 1346":"about 1280–17 October 1346","1280–1346":"1280–1346","1321–1376":"1321–1376","1250–1330":"1250–1330","1346":"1346","17 October 1346":"17 October 1346","1376":"1376","1321":"1321","1330":"1330","1250":"1250","Abt 1280":"about 1280","1280":"1280","Ruthven, Perthshire, Scotland":"Ruthven, Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Ruthven","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name, traditionally pronounced ‘Ri-ven’, from Ruthven by Huntingtower (Perthshire); also possibly from Ruthven (Angus) and various other places of that name throughout Scotland, named either with Gaelic <i>ruadh</i> ‘red’ + <i>mhaighin</i> ‘place’ or with a cognate of Welsh <i>rhudd faen</i> ‘red stone’. The oldest family of this name, the lords of the barony of Ruthven by Perth, were descended from Thor, son of Swain, lord of Tranent in Lothian and first sheriff of Edinburgh on record in the mid 12th century. The family eventually gained the title of Earl of Gowrie, but because of what became known as ‘the Gowrie Conspiracy’ the title was forfeited and from 1600 to 1641 the surname itself was proscribed. The title was later restored to the family, and the present Earl of Gowrie bears the surname <i>Ruthven</i>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William Ruthven Laird of Ruthven was born about 1280, in Ruthven, Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom as the son of Walter Ruthven Laird of Ruthven. He had at least 1 son. He died on 17 October 1346, at the age of 67."},"et":{"Abt 1280–17 October 1346":"umbes 1280–17. oktoober 1346","1280–1346":"1280–1346","1321–1376":"1321–1376","1250–1330":"1250–1330","1346":"1346","17 October 1346":"17. oktoober 1346","1376":"1376","1321":"1321","1330":"1330","1250":"1250","Abt 1280":"umbes 1280","1280":"1280","Ruthven, Perthshire, Scotland":"Ruthven, Perthshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1280–17 October 1346":"noin 1280–17. lokakuuta 1346","1280–1346":"1280–1346","1321–1376":"1321–1376","1250–1330":"1250–1330","1346":"1346","17 October 1346":"17. lokakuuta 1346","1376":"1376","1321":"1321","1330":"1330","1250":"1250","Abt 1280":"noin 1280","1280":"1280","Ruthven, Perthshire, Scotland":"Ruthven, Perthshire, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"Abt 1280–17 October 1346":"environ 1280–17 octobre 1346","1280